# Vue 3 Cursor Rules

## Architecture
- Use Composition API with `<script setup>` syntax (not Options API)
- Organize by feature, not file type: `features/auth/`, `features/dashboard/`
- Use composables (`use*.ts`) for reusable stateful logic
- Prefer single-file components (SFC) with `<script setup lang="ts">`

## Reactivity
- Use `ref()` for primitives, `reactive()` for objects
- Use `computed()` for derived state (cached, re-evaluated when deps change)
- Use `watch()` / `watchEffect()` for side effects
- DON'T: Destructure reactive objects (breaks reactivity) — use `toRefs()`
- DO: Use `shallowRef()` for large objects that don't need deep reactivity

## Component Patterns
- Define props with `defineProps<T>()` for type safety
- Define emits with `defineEmits<T>()` for type-safe events
- Use `defineModel()` for v-model bindings (Vue 3.4+)
- Use `defineExpose()` only when parent needs to access child methods
- Prefer `provide/inject` over prop drilling for deeply nested data

## State Management (Pinia)
- One store per domain: `useUserStore`, `useCartStore`
- Use `storeToRefs()` to destructure store state reactively
- Define stores with Setup syntax for better TypeScript support
- Keep actions async-aware — return promises for loading states

## Performance
- Use `v-memo` for expensive list rendering
- Use `defineAsyncComponent()` for code splitting
- Avoid `v-if` and `v-for` on the same element
- Use `key` attribute on `v-for` with unique IDs (not index)
- Use `<KeepAlive>` for caching component state during tab switching

## Template Best Practices
- Use `v-bind` shorthand: `:prop="value"`
- Use `v-on` shorthand: `@click="handler"`
- Prefer `v-show` over `v-if` for frequently toggled elements
- Use `<Teleport>` for modals, tooltips, dropdowns
- Use `<Transition>` and `<TransitionGroup>` for animations
